755. Cent Eur J Public Health. 2015 Mar;23(1):45-53. doi: 10.21101/cejph.a3996.

Self-perceived health in the czech population: recent evidence.

Kurtinová O.

This article considers developing trends in self-perceptions of health among the 
Czech population. Its conclusions are based on data from the European Union 
Statistics on Income and Living Conditions (EU-SILC) conducted from 2005-2011. 
The data analysis suggests that the compression of morbidity is present, but the 
Czech Republic continues to lag behind Western Europe. In addition, among males 
the difference in health expectancies between the Czech Republic and the EU-15 
is due to a change in mortality at higher ages, rather than in self-perceived 
health. Among females the opposite is true. Demographic categories, such as 
"attained education" and "age-group" proved to be significant factors in 
influencing self-perceived health in the Czech population for the year 2011. 
Gender and marital status seem to be less important.

