Experiments on Hemoglobin in Single Crystals and Silica Gels Distinguish among 
Allosteric Models.

Henry ER(1), Mozzarelli A(2), Viappiani C(3), Abbruzzetti S(4), Bettati S(5), 
Ronda L(5), Bruno S(6), Eaton WA(7).

Author information:
(1)Laboratory of Chemical Physics, NIDDK, National Institutes of Health, 
Bethesda, Maryland.
(2)Institute of Biophysics, CNR, Pisa, Italy; Department of Pharmacy, University 
of Parma, Parma, Italy.
(3)Department of Physics and Earth Sciences, University of Parma, Parma, Italy; 
NEST, Nanoscience Institute, CNR, Pisa, Italy.
(4)NEST, Nanoscience Institute, CNR, Pisa, Italy; Department of Life Sciences, 
University of Parma, Parma, Italy.
(5)Department of Neurosciences, University of Parma, Parma, Italy.
(6)Institute of Biophysics, CNR, Pisa, Italy.
(7)Laboratory of Chemical Physics, NIDDK, National Institutes of Health, 
Bethesda, Maryland. Electronic address: eaton@helix.nih.gov.

Trapping quaternary structures of hemoglobin in single crystals or by 
encapsulation in silica gels has provided a demanding set of data to test 
statistical mechanical models of allostery. In this work, we compare the results 
of those experiments with predictions of the four major allosteric models for 
hemoglobin: the quaternary two-state model of Monod, Wyman, and Changeux; the 
tertiary two-state model of Henry et al., which is the simplest extension of the 
Monod-Wyman-Changeux model to include pre-equilibria of tertiary as well as 
quaternary conformations; the structure-based model of Szabo and Karplus; and 
the modification of the latter model by Lee and Karplus. We show that only the 
tertiary two-state model can provide a near quantitative explanation of the 
single-crystal and gel experimental results.

