[Pregnancy and cystic fibrosis - an overview].

[Article in German]

Michl RK(1), Mues S(2), Mainz JG(1), Markert UR(2).

Author information:
(1)Mukoviszidoszentrum für Kinder und Erwachsene, Klinik für Kinderheilkunde und 
Jugendmedizin, Univeritätsklinikum Jena, Jena.
(2)Abteilung für Geburtshilfe, Universitätsklinikum Jena, Jena.

Life expectancy and quality of life of cystic fibrosis (CF) patients have been 
steadily increasing for many decades, due to intensified therapy and research. 
Correspondingly, the number of pregnancies in women with CF rises. Often it is 
not possible for the patients to assess the consequences of pregnancy in terms 
of their disease and the impact of their disease on the growing child. A 
pre-existing poor lung function, low body mass index, CF-related diabetes, 
chronic microbial colonisation, and transplanted lungs are the main risk factors 
for complications during pregnancy in CF. Generally, the best outcome for mother 
and child can be reached under exact planning and meshed multidisciplinary care. 
The purpose of this summary is to give a practical review of the risks and 
options associated with pregnancy in CF patients.

